<font color="#FF0000">MY COUSIN</font><br>
<tt>Sat Dec  6  9:14:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I was the kid who went to college.  My cousin went to Nam.  I never thought much about it till he came home in 68.  I went to the big city (New York) to welcome him home.  My aunt had placed a big sign stretching across the whole outside front of the house welcoming him home.  I had gone to pick him up at the airport.  He was spit on and repeatedly called a baby-killer.  Welcome home.  First day back and he was already invoved in another war. <br>
I stayed a couple of weeks with him.  Got drunk many nights and just listened and learned.  He was lost and still is today.  I can't help but think we all share the blame.  He grew up on stories of his uncles in World War Two and the Korean War.  He was expected to go.  He did and the experience there and here changed a soft-spoken young man.  We're to blame.  All of us share in the disillusionment of this young man.  He had a right to expect more from us.  Waking up twenty years later is better than not waking up at all but the wait destroyed many fine people like my cousin.
<p><code>--   (Sam) </code><p>


